Exercise 4:

cdc <- transform(cdc, bmi = (weight / height^2) * 703)
boxplot(cdc$bmi ~ cdc$genhlth, xlab = "General health status", ylab = "BMI",
        main = "Distribution of BMI by general health status")

Note: I was asked how to reorder the levels of this factor in class. I will go over this at some point in class, but here is the command:

cdc$genhlth <- factor(cdc$genhlth, levels = c("excellent", "very good", "good", "fair", "poor"))

Now lets recreate the boxplots to see if it worked:

boxplot(cdc$bmi ~ cdc$genhlth, xlab = "General health status", ylab = "BMI",
        main = "Distribution of BMI by general health status")

Most BMIs are roughly between 20 and 30 (over 50% of the data in the healthier groups and about 50% in the fair and poor health groups). We see the median BMI trending upward as health declines. Additionally, the IQRs seem to increase as health declines (i.e.BMIs are more variable).

3:

wdiff is a quantitative variable. If the observed value is 0, then the persons current and desired weight are equal. Negative values of wdiff indicate that the individual wants to lose weight, while positive values indicate that they want to gain weight

4:

# Histogram
hist(cdc$wdiff, col = "gray", breaks = 50, xlab = "Difference between desired and actual weight (in lbs)", main = NULL)

The histogram allows us to see that distribution of the difference between desired weight and current weight is unimodal and symmetric, but is centered below zero (see the summary stats for specifics). This shows that more people want to lose weight than gain weight in the sample.

# Boxplot (notice that I fliped the axes here)
boxplot(cdc$wdiff, horizontal = TRUE, xlab = "Difference between desired and actual weight (in lbs)")

The boxplot highlights the outliers, especially the two overly extreme positive outliers.

# Looking at summary statistics
summary(cdc$wdiff)

Also notice that regardless of the gender, 75% of people in the sample wanted to lose weight (see the 3rd quartile, i.e. .75 quantile).

6:

My approach to this problem is to create new objects to store the mean (xbar) and standard deviation (s), create a new variable that is TRUE if the weight is within one standard deviation of the mean and FALSE otherwise. Then, taking the mean yields the proportion since TRUE is interpreted as a 1 and FALSE is interpreted as a 0.

# Summary stats
xbar <- mean(cdc$weight)
s <- sd(cdc$weight)


# Creating a TRUE/FALSE variable for being with one sd of the mean
cdc <- transform(cdc, one_sd_weight = weight >= xbar - s & weight <= xbar + s)

# Now you can take the mean of TRUE/FALSE (TRUE = 1, FALSE = 0)
mean(cdc$one_sd_weight)
## [1] 0.7076

70.76% of the weights are within one standard deviation of the mean.
